{
id: "44fcdfa534e63875",
category: "General Pharmacology",
subcategory: "04-pyqs",
tags: ["ZVRecommended", "PYQ", "INI-CET Nov 2024"],
text: "A 52-year-old female presents with metastatic breast cancer. She has previously undergone treatment with surgery, radiation, and multiple lines of chemotherapy, but her disease has progressed. Genetic testing reveals a BRCA1 mutation, indicating an impaired DNA repair mechanism. Her cancer is classified as HER2-negative and hormone receptor-positive. Given the genetic findings, her oncologist considers using a therapy that targets the PARP enzyme to exploit the DNA repair vulnerability of her cancer cells. Which of the following drugs would be appropriate to prescribe as a PARP inhibitor in this patient?",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Palbociclib", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "B", "text": "Rucaparib", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "C", "text": "Vorinostat", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "D", "text": "Ustekinumab", "is_correct": false}],
explanation: "**BRCA mutation = defective DNA repair system**\nNormal cells repair DNA via 2 major pathways:<br><br>* **BRCA (Homologous recombination)** \u2192 repairs double-strand breaks\n* **PARP pathway** \u2192 repairs single-strand breaks<br><br>BRCA-mutated tumors have defective homologous recombination repair and are sensitive to **PARP inhibition** via synthetic lethality. Rucaparib is a PARP inhibitor that blocks DNA repair, causing tumor cell death. Palbociclib is a CDK4/6 inhibitor, vorinostat is an HDAC inhibitor, and ustekinumab is an immunologic agent. Targeting PARP exploits the DNA repair defect in BRCA cancers.<br><br>| **Drug** | **Target** | **Use** |\n| ---- | ------ | --- |\n| Rucaparib | PARP | BRCA cancers |\n| Palbociclib | CDK4/6 | Breast cancer |\n| Trastuzumab | HER2 | HER2+ cancer |\n| Imatinib | BCR-ABL | CML |<br><br>",
images: []
},
{
id: "6eb03e8d9c5d851d",
category: "General Pharmacology",
subcategory: "04-pyqs",
tags: ["ZVRecommended", "PYQ", "INI-CET May 2025"],
text: "Which of the following statements regarding thalidomide is false?",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "It acts as an antimetabolite", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "B", "text": "It is a teratogenic drug", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "C", "text": "It is used in type 2 lepra reaction (ENL)", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "D", "text": "It is used in relapsing multiple myeloma", "is_correct": false}],
explanation: "Thalidomide has a unique pharmacologic profile combining immunomodulatory, anti-angiogenic, and notorious teratogenic properties, with several established clinical uses despite its historical toxicity.<br><br>Evaluating each statement:<br><br>* It is a teratogenic drug – True. Thalidomide is infamous for causing severe limb defects (phocomelia) and other congenital malformations when used in pregnancy.\n* It is used in type 2 lepra reaction (ENL) – True. Thalidomide is an established and effective treatment for erythema nodosum leprosum (ENL), a type 2 lepra reaction, due to its anti-TNF-alpha and immunomodulatory effects.\n* It is used in relapsing multiple myeloma – True. Thalidomide (and its analogs lenalidomide, pomalidomide) is used in multiple myeloma due to its anti-angiogenic and immunomodulatory actions on the bone marrow microenvironment.<br><br>Why 'acts as an antimetabolite' is false:<br><br>* Thalidomide does **not** act as an antimetabolite. Its mechanism involves **anti-angiogenesis** (inhibiting VEGF and bFGF-mediated angiogenesis), **immunomodulation** (altering cytokine production, including TNF-alpha inhibition), and modulation of cereblon-mediated protein degradation — it does not interfere with metabolic pathways or nucleotide synthesis as classic antimetabolites (e.g., methotrexate, 5-FU) do.<br><br>Why other options are incorrect:<br><br>* Teratogenicity, use in ENL, and use in relapsing multiple myeloma are all true, well-established facts about thalidomide, making them inappropriate answers to this 'false statement' question.",
images: []
},
{
id: "ecce53c4bf64920d",
category: "General Pharmacology",
subcategory: "04-pyqs",
tags: ["PYQ", "INI-CET Nov 2025"],
text: "Which of the following drugs acts on VEGF (Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor)?",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Pembrolizumab", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "B", "text": "Ipilimumab", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "C", "text": "Ramucirumab", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "D", "text": "Dostarlimab", "is_correct": false}],
explanation: "Tumors are greedy, to survive, they **stimulate new blood vessel formation (angiogenesis)** using: **VEGF (Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor)**<br><br>Ramucirumab is a monoclonal antibody against **VEGF receptor-2**, blocking VEGF-mediated angiogenesis. It inhibits tumor blood vessel formation and growth. Pembrolizumab, ipilimumab, and dostarlimab are immune checkpoint inhibitors targeting PD-1 or CTLA-4, not VEGF.<br><br>| **Option** | **Drug** | **Target** | **Why Wrong** |\n| ------ | ---- | ------ | --------- |\n| A | Pembrolizumab | PD-1 | Immune checkpoint inhibitor |\n| B | Ipilimumab | CTLA-4 | T-cell activation \u2191 |\n| D | Dostarlimab | PD-1 | Used in MSI-high tumors |<br><br>Anti-angiogenic action is the key distinguishing feature of ramucirumab.",
images: []
}
